## Preparing the SSP Review Package

The SSP review package submitted to the AO for Task S-6 contains more than just the SSP document. A complete review package allows the AO to evaluate the system's security posture with full context.

**Core documents:**

*System Security Plan (current version):* The complete SSP as developed through Days 43-52, including all sections: system description, categorization, tailored control set, allocation record, implementation descriptions for all controls (technical and administrative), and continuous monitoring strategy.

*Risk Assessment Summary:* The risk register from Day 38 (RS-001 through RS-007) with current status — noting which risk scenarios have controls implemented, which have controls planned (POA&M), and what the residual risk level is for each scenario after controls are applied.

*Plan of Action and Milestones (POA&M):* The current POA&M documenting all identified gaps: clinical downtime procedures (CP-2), IR technical response simulation (IR-3), CloudWatch patient-record-level anomaly queries (AU-6), and the alternate processing site test (CP-4). Each POA&M item includes the owner, target remediation date, compensating controls in place during the remediation period, and residual risk during the gap period.

*Control Allocation Summary Table:* The one-page summary from Day 49 showing how controls are distributed across Common (AWS), System-Specific (MyClinic), and Hybrid categories. This gives the AO a clear picture of where MyClinic's security responsibility lies versus what is inherited from AWS.

*Categorization Approval Record:* The signed categorization approval from Day 45 showing that the High categorization was reviewed and approved by the System Owner, Privacy Officer, Compliance Officer, and AO at the time of the categorization decision.

**Executive Summary (prepared specifically for the AO):**

The executive summary is not the same as the SSP introduction. It is written for an audience that needs to understand the security posture without reading the full technical documentation. The executive summary for the OpenMRS SSP covers:

*What the system is and why it matters:* OpenMRS is the sole EHR system for MyClinic — the only authoritative record of patient health information. Its security directly affects patient safety and organizational compliance.

*What the risk level is:* HIGH. The highest impact category for all three security objectives. This drives the most rigorous control baseline and the most intensive monitoring and assessment requirements.

*What the biggest risks are and how they are addressed:* The three highest-priority risk scenarios are ransomware (RS-001), web application exploit (RS-002), and insider PHI misuse (RS-004). MFA for all users, WAF deployment, and automated audit logging with anomaly detection are the primary controls addressing these scenarios.

*What is not yet fully implemented:* Four POA&M items are open. The most significant is clinical downtime procedures — the absence of tested procedures for clinical operations during EHR unavailability is the primary driver of the High availability categorization. The POA&M target for this item is [date], before the authorization package is finalized.

*What the monitoring commitment is:* Continuous automated monitoring via GuardDuty and AWS Config; daily backup and authentication review; weekly CloudTrail analysis; monthly vulnerability scanning; quarterly access recertification and backup restoration testing; annual security assessment.

