## A Real-World Example That Made This Click

While reviewing the AO risk acceptance discussion today I came across the circumstances of the **2014 OPM breach** — which I covered on Day 42 from the system registration angle — but want to revisit through the SSP review and AO accountability lens.

OPM's breach, which exposed the records of 21.5 million federal employees and contractors, occurred in an environment where the federal Inspector General had repeatedly flagged security deficiencies in OPM's systems in prior audit reports. Some of the systems that were breached were operating under expired authorizations — meaning the ATO had lapsed and the system was running without a current, valid authorization.

The connection to today's task is specific: the ATO process requires AO review of the security posture and formal risk acceptance. When systems operate on expired ATOs, no one has formally reviewed and accepted the risk of continued operation in the current security state. The controls may have drifted from what was originally assessed. New vulnerabilities may have been discovered. The system may have changed in ways that were not reflected in the SSP.

OPM's IG audit findings — which flagged authorization lapses and security deficiencies — were exactly the kind of signals that should have triggered SSP reviews and updated authorizations. The failure to act on those findings meant the formal risk acceptance process that the ATO is designed to enforce was not functioning.

For MyClinic's OpenMRS authorization, the lesson is about treating the authorization as a living commitment, not a one-time event. The SSP approval today is the first formal risk acceptance. Annual security assessments, continuous monitoring results reviewed by the AO, and prompt response to POA&M items are what keep that risk acceptance current and meaningful over the life of the system.

