## What I Am Still Thinking About

One aspect of the AO review that I want to think through more carefully: how should the AO handle the POA&M items during the authorization decision?

Standard RMF practice allows systems to receive ATOs with open POA&M items — the ATO represents risk acceptance that accounts for the residual risk from those open items. The AO is accepting not just the risk of the implemented controls, but the additional residual risk from what is not yet implemented.

For OpenMRS at MyClinic, the most significant open POA&M item — clinical downtime procedures — creates real availability risk. The question I am still thinking about is: should the AO grant an unconditional ATO with the downtime procedures as an open POA&M item, or should the authorization be conditioned on downtime procedure completion?

My instinct is that an unconditional ATO for a High-impact system with an open POA&M item that directly affects the availability categorization rationale is hard to defend. If the availability impact was rated High partly because downtime procedures do not exist, and the ATO is granted without those procedures, the AO has accepted a higher level of availability risk than the categorization analysis assumed.

A conditional ATO — or an IATT that converts to a full ATO when the downtime procedures are complete and tested — seems more appropriate. I want to raise this explicitly with the AO rather than leaving it as an implicit assumption that the open POA&M is acceptable as-is.

